\layout Title

A Family of 4-point Dyadic High Resolution Subdivision Schemes
\layout Author

Daniel Lemire
\layout Abstract

By using temporary placeholders on a dense grid, we generalize the 4-point
 dyadic cubic Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme.
 Interpolated values require 2 steps to stabilize as they are first interpolated
 on a coarse scale through a tetradic filter and then on a finer scale using
 a dyadic filter.
 The interpolants are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset 

 and can be made to reproduce polynomials of degree 4.
 These generalized interpolatory subdivision schemes have minimal support
 and no additional memory requirement.
 This work has applications in CAGD and wavelet theory.
\layout Keywords

Subdivision Schemes, Fourier transform, CAGD, Wavelets, Lagrange Interpolation
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

Interpolatory subdivision schemes interpolate a discrete set of data points
 in a local manner, that is, the value of the interpolation function at
 a given point depends on a small number of nearby data points.
 The classical dyadic algorithm introduced by Deslauriers and Dubuc 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Du,DeDu}

\end_inset 

 finds the midpoint values by fitting a Lagrange polynomial through the
 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset 

 closest data points.
 By repeating this algorithm again and again, each time doubling the number
 of data points or nodes by midpoint interpolation, we eventually have a
 dense set of data points and can determine uniquely a smooth interpolation
 function.
 Because interpolatory subdivision schemes relate data points from one scale
 to another scale, it is not surprising that they are a key ingredient in
 the construction of compactly supported wavelets 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Dau,DeDuLe}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

More recently, Merrien 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Me92,Me99,DuLeMe}

\end_inset 

 introduced Hermite subdivision schemes.
 Since Merrien subdivision schemes use Hermite nodes, they have have twice
 the approximation order and better regularity for a given support.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $2-$
\end_inset 

point Hermite schemes are differentiable and can reproduce quadratic or
 cubic polynomials whereas the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $2-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme (the linear spline) isn't differentiable
 and only reproduces linear polynomials.
 
\layout Standard

Since Deslauriers-Dubuc schemes have important applications, it is tempting
 to add extra nodes to Deslauriers and Dubuc schemes as an attempt to improve
 them to get 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

high resolution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 schemes.
 Doubling the number of nodes is costly: it doubles the memory requirements.
 However, since a dyadic subdivision scheme doubles its memory usage at
 each step, we can choose to use right away this upcoming extra storage
 space without any cost.
 In effect, we can simply make use of the memory that will be allocated
 later in any case.
 Therefore, we can freely increase the number of nodes in intermediate steps.
 These new placeholders can then be used to record a coarse scale guess
 (using a tetradic filter) which we can later combine with a finer scale
 interpolation (using a dyadic filter).
 These schemes are said to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

high resolution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 because we no longer consider only the next finer scale, but actually the
 next two finer scales; alternatively, we could describe these algorithms
 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

two-step subdivision schemes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 As a special case, we may choose to ignore the coarse scale estimate, in
 which case the high resolution scheme is equivalent to a Deslauriers-Dubuc
 scheme; we can also use this family of schemes to reproduce polynomials
 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset 

 by a Richardson extrapolation approach.
 The main result of this paper is that by summing up the tetradic (coarse)
 interpolation recorded in placeholders and dyadic (fine) interpolations,
 we get a range of smooth (
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset 

) high resolutions schemes reproducing cubic polynomials.
\layout Section

Subdivision schemes
\layout Standard

Interpolatory subdivision schemes where first introduced by Deslauriers
 and Dubuc 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Du,DeDu}

\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b>1$
\end_inset 

 be an integer then given two integers 
\begin_inset Formula $k,j$
\end_inset 

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j,k}=k/b^{j}$
\end_inset 

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic (of depth 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

).
 For a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic numbers form a regularly spaced set of nodes.
 For a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset 

, given some data 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{J,k}\right\} _{k\in\Z}$
\end_inset 

, we want to build a smooth fonction 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{J,k}\right)=y_{J,k}\,\forall k\in\Z$
\end_inset 

.
 Starting with this initial data (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{J,k}$
\end_inset 

) and using the linear formula 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum_{k\in\Z}\gamma_{bk-l}y_{j,k}\label{basicsubdivision}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for some constant array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

, we get values 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $j>J$
\end_inset 

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic numbers form a dense set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset 

, there is at most one continuous function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{j,k}\right)=y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\Z,j>J$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

A subdivision scheme is interpolatory and satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{J,k}\right)=y_{J,k}$
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{bk}=0\,\forall k\in\Z$
\end_inset 

 except for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}=1$
\end_inset 

.
 We say that a subdivision scheme is stationary if the array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 is constant (doesn't depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

).
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 doesn't depend explicitely on 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 the scheme is translation invariant or homogeneous.
 An interpolatory subdivision scheme is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{l}=0$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $|l|>Nb$
\end_inset 

.
 The interpolation function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 computed from a 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic scheme with initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,k}=0$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq0$
\end_inset 

 is said to be the fundamental function and has a compact support of 
\begin_inset Formula $[-(Nb-1)/(b-1),(Nb-1)/(b-1)]$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-2N,2N-1]$
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset 

.
 Hence as 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

 increases the support of the fundamental function increases.
\layout Standard

For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1,2,3,...$
\end_inset 

 there are corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point interpolatory Deslauriers-Dubuc subdivision schemes and they are built
 from the midpoint evaluation of Lagrange polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-1$
\end_inset 

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset 

 (dyadic case), the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme can be defined from the array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{DD2}$
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}^{DD2}=1,\,$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1}^{DD2}=\gamma_{-1}^{DD2}=-9/16,\,$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{3}^{DD2}=\gamma_{-3}^{DD2}=-1/16$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}^{DD2}=0$
\end_inset 

 otherwise; for 
\begin_inset Formula $b=4$
\end_inset 

 (tetradic case), the scheme is defined from the array 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{DD4}$
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma_{k}^{DD2}\,\forall k\in\Z,\,$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{-1}^{DD4}=\gamma_{1}^{DD4}=105/128,\,$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{-3}^{DD4}=\gamma_{-3}^{DD4}=35/128,\,$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{-5}^{DD4}=\gamma_{5}^{DD4}=-7/128,\,$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{-7}^{DD4}=\gamma_{7}^{DD4}=-5/128,\,$
\end_inset 

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}^{DD2}=0$
\end_inset 

 otherwise.
 
\layout Standard

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc schemes are derived from cubic Lagrange polynomials,
 they reproduce cubic polynomials, that is, if the initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}=p\left(x_{j,k}\right)\,\forall k\in\Z$
\end_inset 

 for some cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 then the interpolation function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 is this same cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f=p$
\end_inset 

.
 The two cases presented above (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{DD2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{DD4}$
\end_inset 

) reproduce cubic polynomials and it can also be shown that they both give
 differentiable (
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset 

) interpolation functions.
 Because we later borrow from these two subdivision schemes, we give explicit
 algorithms for both schemes.
